    researchFindings: ["BPC-157, the most studied pentadecapeptide, has shown tissue-protective effects across multiple organ systems in animal models.","Research demonstrated that the 15-amino acid sequence retains full biological activity of the larger parent gastric protein.","Studies on synthetic pentadecapeptides have identified antimicrobial sequences with activity against resistant pathogens.","The 15-amino acid length represents an optimal balance between structural complexity and synthetic accessibility for drug development.","Various pentadecapeptides have shown ability to modulate growth factor expression and cellular repair pathways."],
    risks: ["Safety profiles vary significantly between different pentadecapeptide sequences.","Most research is preclinical; human clinical data is limited for most pentadecapeptides.","Quality control for synthetic peptides from unregulated sources is a concern.","Potential for immune responses to exogenous peptide administration.","Long-term effects of repeated peptide administration are not well characterized."],
    administration: "Administration varies by specific pentadecapeptide. BPC-157 is typically administered via subcutaneous injection at 250-500 mcg once or twice daily, or orally for GI applications. Other pentadecapeptides have different dosing protocols depending on their specific application. Routes include subcutaneous, intramuscular, oral, and topical.",
    legalStatus: "Pentadecapeptides as a class are not regulated uniformly. BPC-157 is available as a research chemical. Other pentadecapeptides may fall under various regulatory categories depending on their intended use. Not controlled substances. Regulatory status depends on the specific peptide and jurisdiction.",
